"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the UK Energy Research Centre (HOT28)&#xa0;the UK Energy Research Centre&#xa0;\nThe UK Energy Research Centre carries out world-class research into sustainable future energy systems.\n&#xa0;\nIt is the hub \nof UK energy research and the gateway between the UK and the international energy research communities. Our interdisciplinary, whole systems research informs UK policy development and research strategy.\n&#xa0;\nExecutive Summary\n&#xa0;\nUKERC Response to Questions\n&#xa0;\nQuestion 1 - Is the government taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 2 - What progress is the government making on reducing carbon emissions from the demand for heat?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 3 - Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives.  What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture? \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nQuestion 4 - There are sustainability guidelines for biomass, do these go far enough?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 5 - What will the local environmental impact (for example air pollution) be from the use of heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 6 - What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating compared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 7 - Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 8 - What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 9 - Should the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 10 - Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 11 - How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?&#xa0;&#xa0;\nQuestion 12 - Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand both diurnally and annually.  What is government policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?&#xa0;Re\nferen\nces\n&#xa0;\n[1]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLowe, R. (2011). “Combined heat and power considered as a virtual steam cycle heat pump.” Energy Policy UK 39, pp 5528–5534\n.\n[2]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSansom, R; Strbac, G. (2012). “The impact of future heat demand pathways on the economics of low carbon heating systems.” BIEE\n – 9\nth\n Academic \nConference - European Energy in a Challenging World: The impact of emerging markets. St John's College, Oxford. 19/20 September 2012\n.\n[3]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRosenow, J.; Eyre, N. (2012). “The Green Deal and the Energy Company Obligation – will it work?”  9th BIEE\n Academic Conference - European Energy in a Challenging World: The impact of emerging markets. St John's College, Oxford. 19/20 September 2012\n.\n[4]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSorrell, S. (2007). “The Rebound Effect: an assessment of the evidence for economy-wide energy savings.” UKERC. \nLondon. UK.\n[5]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIEA Bioenergy. (2011). “Using a life cycle assessment approach to estimate the net greenhouse gas emissions of bioenergy.” IEA Bioenergy: ExCo:\n \n2011:\n \n03.\n[6]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nZanchi, G.; Pena, N.; Bird, D.N. (2010). “The upfront carbon debt of bioenergy.” Report fo\nr Birdlife International by Joanneum Research.  \nwww.birdlife.org/eu/pdfs/Bioenergy_Joanneum_Research.pdf\n \n[7]\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDECC. (2013). “Domestic Renewable Heat Incentive: The first step to tr\nansforming the way we heat our homes.\n” DECC\n.\n London\n,\n \nUK.\n[8]\n&#